\begin{description}
	\item[4.1]
      The mean filter is an LTI system (or more properly a Linear Space-Invariant system), because it is just a low-pass filter in two dimensions.
      Formally:\\
      $x(a,b)\rightarrow y(n)=\frac{1}{9}\sum_{i=-2}^{2}\sum_{j=-2}^{2}x(a-i,b-j)$\\
      $Ax_1(a,b)+Bx_2(a,b)\rightarrow y(n)=A\frac{1}{9}\sum_{i=-2}^{2}\sum_{j=-2}^{2}x_1(a-i,b-j)+B\frac{1}{9}\sum_{i=-2}^{2}\sum_{j=-2}^{2}x_2(a-i,b-j)=Ay_1(a,b)+By_2(a,b)$\\
      $y(a-\tau_a,b-\tau_b)=\frac{1}{9}\sum_{i=-2}^{2}\sum_{j=-2}^{2}x(a-i-\tau_a,b-j-\tau_b)$\\
      $\hat{y}(a-\tau_a,b-\tau_b)=\frac{1}{9}\sum_{i=-2}^{2}\sum_{j=-2}^{2}x(a-i-\tau_a,b-j-\tau_b)=y(a-\tau_a,b-\tau_b)$
      $\implies LTI$
	\item[4.2]
      The median filter is not LTI.\\
      Take, for example, a 3 by 3 image, a(x,y), that takes the following values:\\
          \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}\hline
            622 & 166 & 149 \\\hline
            482 & 845 & 779 \\\hline
            828 & 23 & 667 \\\hline
          \end{tabular}\\
      This array has a median of 622.\\
      And another 3 by 3 image, b(x,y), that takes the following values:\\
          \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}\hline
            327 & 113 & 568 \\\hline
            541 & 899 & 437 \\\hline
            949 & 743 & 623 \\\hline
          \end{tabular}\\
      This array has a median of 568.\\
      But the following signal is a+b:\\
          \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}\hline
            949 & 279 & 717 \\\hline
            1023 & 1744 & 1216 \\\hline
            1817 & 816 & 1290 \\\hline
          \end{tabular}\\
      This array has a median of 1023.
      $622+568=1190\neq1023$
      So the median filter fails the superposition property of linearity, and is not LTI.
	\item[4.6]
      The median filter does a better job at removing the noise in the image without destroying quality.
      This is the case because the noisy particles tend to add skewing to the image data in the window.
      In statistics, generally, median serves better as the center of a distribution that is not normal.
      Since median is positional, it is more resistant to both noise and outliers like the noise added to the Lena image.
      Mean, on the other hand, is heavily skewed by outliers.
      Since median minimizes the effects of the outliers, it does a better job at eliminating noise.
\end{description}

